Suwa Shrine is believed to have been founded in {{ill|1390|ja|1390th year|qq=draft|qq=draft}} ({{ill|Meitoku|ja|明徳|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 1){{sfn|Edo Meisho Zue|1927|p=591}}. It was established by Umehonbo Jokan, the bettō (chief priest) of the nearby {{ill|Kitano Shrine (Bunkyo-ku)|ja|北野神社 (文京区)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who enshrined a spirit from {{ill|Suwa Taisha|ja|諏訪大社|1=Suwa-taisha|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in his birthplace, {{ill|Shinano Province|ja|信濃国|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Suwa District|ja|諏訪郡|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Due to this connection, Suwa Shrine remains an auxiliary shrine of Kitano Shrine<ref name="shrine">Kazunori Uchiumi (ed.), "Bunkyo-ku Jinja-shi," Bunkyo Ward Shrine General Assembly, 1988, pp. 39-40, 401-403</ref>.

== Sessha and Massha (Subordinate Shrines) ==
